detaileddescription.para: deliberately deleted. If you try using the builder interface (chaining setter methods) from a default instantiated PhysicalEntity you will get an error, because there will be no model assicated with PhysicalEntity. Instead, always instantiate a PhysicalEntity from the Editor::addPhysicalEntity() method.

detaileddescription.para: PhysicalEntity objects are owned either by the caller or by a Triples object, depending on whether you have "given" the PhysicalEntity to a Triples object by calling "str" or "toTriples".

This alternative constructor is used when users use the builder interface (which should actually be most of the time). The PhysicalEntity is instantiated with only the model to allow for a better way of collecting necessary information from the user.

briefdescription.para: constructor for PhysicalEntity object.

detaileddescription.para:
model
the librdf_model object in use. Passed down from Editor class during instantiation.
model_uri
the current localName argument. Passed down from Editor
This alternative constructor is used when users use the builder interface (which should actually be most of the time). The PhysicalEntity is instantiated with only the model to allow for a better way of collecting necessary information from the user. The PhysicalEntity also needs access to the model_uri, which we pass here.

briefdescription.para: convert PhysicalEntity to a Triples object, which can then be passed to a model via the Editor::addPhysicalEntity method.

detaileddescription.para:
a Triples objects containing the Triple objects associated with this PhysicalEntity
When using "toTriples" you are giving ownership of the nodes used by PhysicalEntity to the returned Triples object, which automatically cleans up after itself in its destructor. If you instantiate a PhysicalEntity and do not call toTriples (which will not be often), then the caller is responsible for calling PhysicalEntity::free when finished.

resource

briefdescription.para: alias for setIdentity
add a location to the PhysicalEntity.

detaileddescription.para:
where
The resource representing a location.
a reference to this Physical entity. Allows chaining together builder commands.
The input string gets converted to a Resource automatically. An arbitrary number of locations are allowed. The location is added to the back of a vector containing the Resources. Left most elements of this vector represent larger physiological locations which get smaller as the index of this vector increases via use of the "isPartOf" predicate. For example, a cytosolic TGFb molecule in a dermal fibroblast could have a locations vector first containing a reference to skin, then dermis, then fibroblast, then cytosol. This ends up being cytosol<isPartOf>fibroblast<isPartOf>dermis<isPartOf>skin.
See Resource documentation for more details of valid input strings.

parameterdescription.para: the string to be used for is. This should be of the form OPB:OPB_00134 This function calls the PhysicalEntity::setIdentity method and can be used as an alternative. For developers, consider which (or both? )sets of methods to keep, is or setIdentity

This should be of the form fma:FMA:12345 or fma/FMA:12345 This function calls the PhysicalEntity::addLocation method and can be used as an alternative. For developers, consider which (or both? )sets of methods to keep, addLocation or isPartOf
